    description: "Leishmaniasis is a parasitic disease caused by the protozoan Leishmania parasite, which is transmitted to humans through the bite of infected female sandflies. It is classified into three main forms: visceral leishmaniasis (VL, or Kala-azar), which is the most severe and fatal form affecting internal organs; cutaneous leishmaniasis (CL), causing skin sores; and mucocutaneous leishmaniasis (MCL), affecting the nose, mouth, and throat. Kala-azar is endemic in parts of India, particularly Bihar.",
    symptoms: "Visceral Leishmaniasis (Kala-azar) is characterized by a prolonged, irregular fever that can last for weeks or months, significant weight loss, enlargement of the spleen (splenomegaly) and liver (hepatomegaly), and anemia. The skin may become dark and dry, giving the disease its name ('Black Fever'). Cutaneous Leishmaniasis presents as one or more skin lesions, typically ulcers, that can leave permanent scars.",
